<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>ROS2 Tutorial Pages on Dan Aukes</title><link>https://www.danaukes.com/notebook/ros2/</link><description>Recent content in ROS2 Tutorial Pages on Dan Aukes</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Sun, 17 Sep 2023 00:00:00 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://www.danaukes.com/notebook/ros2/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Installing ROS2 Humble on two Virtualbox VMs</title><link>https://www.danaukes.com/notebook/ros2/10-installing-ros2-on-a-vm/</link><pubDate>Sun, 17 Sep 2023 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://www.danaukes.com/notebook/ros2/10-installing-ros2-on-a-vm/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="introduction">Introduction&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>How do you get a ROS2 system up and running on a virtual machine, and participating on your local network as if it were a real pc? This tutorial helps you set up two virtual machine clones that can talk to each other without any special hardware other than your own pc, but look to any other device on the ROS network as if they are two full-fledged computers&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Installing ROS2 on a Raspberry Pi</title><link>https://www.danaukes.com/notebook/ros2/11-installing-ros2-on-a-rpiz2w/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://www.danaukes.com/notebook/ros2/11-installing-ros2-on-a-rpiz2w/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="flashing">Flashing&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>Make sure you&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>add your ssh key during flashing&lt;/li>
&lt;li>setup wifi&lt;/li>
&lt;li>define a hostname&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;h2 id="tailscale">Tailscale&lt;/h2>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>turn on magicdns&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#272822;background-color:#fafafa;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>sudo tailscale &lt;span style="color:#111">set&lt;/span> --operator&lt;span style="color:#f92672">=&lt;/span>&lt;span style="color:#111">$USER&lt;/span> -accept-dns&lt;span style="color:#f92672">=&lt;/span>&lt;span style="color:#111">true&lt;/span> --accept-routes&lt;span style="color:#f92672">=&lt;/span>&lt;span style="color:#111">true&lt;/span> 
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/div>&lt;h2 id="installing">Installing&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>It&amp;rsquo;s important to disable automatic updates as you should initiate it according to your own availability. Otherwise, it will start updating the first time you get an internet connection. To prevent that, uninstall the &amp;ldquo;unattended-upgrades&amp;rdquo; package.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Demonstrating Unicast in ROS2 on virtual machines over a local network using CycloneDDS</title><link>https://www.danaukes.com/notebook/ros2/20-configuring-unicast-dds-with-cyclone/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://www.danaukes.com/notebook/ros2/20-configuring-unicast-dds-with-cyclone/</guid><description>&lt;p>Switching from ROS2&amp;rsquo;s multicast default to unicast can be a bit tricky, especially if you&amp;rsquo;re testing. I came up with a way to get it working between to virtualbox virtual machine clones and wanted to share my strategy.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Demonstrating Unicast in ROS2 on two docker containers with CycloneDDS</title><link>https://www.danaukes.com/notebook/ros2/21-configuring-two-docker-containers-with-unicast-local/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://www.danaukes.com/notebook/ros2/21-configuring-two-docker-containers-with-unicast-local/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="introduction">Introduction&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>In other articles I have shown how to configure a virtual machine to talk over cycloneDDS using unicast rather than the default multicast. This article details the steps required to do the same in docker. Docker is much lighter weight to set up than a virtual machine, and is a useful choice if you want to test your network.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Configuring ROS2 over a Tailscale VPN on Ubuntu</title><link>https://www.danaukes.com/notebook/ros2/30-configuring-ros-over-tailscale/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://www.danaukes.com/notebook/ros2/30-configuring-ros-over-tailscale/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="prerequisites">Prerequisites&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>This tutorial assumes you have already installed ROS2 on a PC, Raspberry pi, or virtual machine running Ubuntu. For those tutorials, please see:&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Using ROS2 over tailscale using Docker's Host-mode networking</title><link>https://www.danaukes.com/notebook/ros2/31-using-ros2-on-docker-over-tailscale-host-mode/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://www.danaukes.com/notebook/ros2/31-using-ros2-on-docker-over-tailscale-host-mode/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="introduction">Introduction&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>This example shows you how to create a docker-compose based container that uses &amp;ldquo;host-mode&amp;rdquo; networking. Host mode networking can be simpler because it doesn&amp;rsquo;t have to be managed by docker itself. Just get your tailscale client up and running on the host computer, and your docker instance can use it.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Using ROS2 in a Docker container running Tailscale</title><link>https://www.danaukes.com/notebook/ros2/32-using-ros2-on-docker-over-tailscale-container/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://www.danaukes.com/notebook/ros2/32-using-ros2-on-docker-over-tailscale-container/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="introduction">Introduction&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>This example shows you how to create a docker-compose based container that uses tailscale which has been installed within a container.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Setting up Rosbridge in Ubuntu</title><link>https://www.danaukes.com/notebook/ros2/40-getting-rosbridge-running/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://www.danaukes.com/notebook/ros2/40-getting-rosbridge-running/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="introduction">Introduction&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>Rosbridge is useful for connecting non-ROS systems to ROS. Matlab, microcontrollers, and other systems often do not have an easy path for installing a full installation of ROS, but have ros-bridge clients that work with Rosbridge. This article shows the following:&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Setting up Rosbridge in a docker container</title><link>https://www.danaukes.com/notebook/ros2/41-setting-up-rosbridge-on-docker/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://www.danaukes.com/notebook/ros2/41-setting-up-rosbridge-on-docker/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="introduction">Introduction&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>This article shows the following:&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>how to get rosbridge working in a docker container&lt;/li>
&lt;li>How to create a custom user in a dockerfile&lt;/li>
&lt;li>how to set up rosbridge for use with a physical network, even one through a wifi NIC (which has historically been harder)&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;h2 id="folder-structure">Folder structure&lt;/h2>
&lt;pre tabindex="0">&lt;code>.
├── build
│   ├── Dockerfile
